'''Ivan Šunjić''' (born 9 October 1996) is a Bosnian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[defensive midfielder]] for [[Cyprus First Division]] club [[Pafos FC|Pafos]] and the [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina national team]].

Šunjić previously played for [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] and [[NK Lokomotiva|Lokomotiva]] in Croatia, before joining English club [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] in 2019. He spent the 2022–23 season on [[Loan (association football)|loan]] to [[Bundesliga]] club [[Hertha BSC]], and was released at the end of the 2023–24 season. Following his release from Birmingham City, Šunjić joined the Cypriot club Pafos in August 2024, helping the club to achieve their first league title in his debut season.

Šunjić is of Croat descent and was born in Bosnia and Herzegovina, and emigrated to Croatia as a young child. He played for Croatia's youth teams from [[Croatia national under-16 football team|under-16]] to [[Croatia national under-21 football team|under-21 level]] and [[Cap (association football)|played]] once for the [[Croatia national football team|senior team]] in 2017. In 2024, Šunjić switched his allegiance to Bosnia and Herzegovina.

==Early life==
Šunjić was born on 9 October 1996 in [[Zenica]], Bosnia and Herzegovina.<ref name="Dinamo Profile">{{cite web |url=https://gnkdinamo.hr/HR/Players/Single?Permalink=ivan-sunjic1 |title=Ivan Šunjić |publisher=Dinamo Zagreb |access-date=26 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726102242/https://gnkdinamo.hr/HR/Players/Single?Permalink=ivan-sunjic1 |archive-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> He and his family{{snd}}father Jozo, mother Aleksandra, and older brother Nikola<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sportske.jutarnji.hr/sn/nogomet/nogomet-mix/odlazi-odavde-kako-je-jedan-nas-nekad-slavni-klub-zbog-nevjerojatno-bizarnog-razloga-potjerao-hrvatskog-reprezentativca-9167159 |title='Odlazi ovdade!' Kako je jedan naš nekad slavni klub zbog nevjerojatno bizarnog razloga potjerao hrvatskog reprezentativca |language=hr |trans-title='Get out of here!' How one of our once famous clubs chased a Croatian international for an incredibly bizarre reason |first=Davorin |last=Olivari |newspaper=Jutarnji list |location=Zagreb |date=26 July 2019 |access-date=17 November 2024}}</ref> {{snd}}moved from their home in [[Kakanj]] to [[Zagreb]], Croatia, in 2000.<ref name="Dnveni bilten">{{cite news |url=https://dnevnibilten.com/ivan-sunjic-novi-zmaj/ |title=Ivan Šunjić novi Zmaj |language=bs |trans-title=Ivan Šunjić the new Dragon |first=Kemal |last=Smailagić |newspaper=Dnevni bilten |location=Kakanj, Bosnia |date=14 November 2024 |access-date=17 November 2024}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Early career===
Šunjić began his football career in the youth ranks of [[NK Špansko]]. He moved to [[NK Zagreb]] in 2009, and joined [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] at cadet level in 2012.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.kicker.de/ivan-sunjic/laufbahn |title=Ivan Sunjic: Laufbahn |language=de |trans-title=Ivan Sunjic: Timeline|magazine=Kicker|access-date=17 November 2024}}</ref><ref name="Semafor">{{cite web |url=https://semafor.hns.family/igraci/99401/ivan-sunjic/ |title=Semafor: Ivan Šunjić: Statistika po sezonama |language=hr |trans-title=Semafor: Ivan Šunjić: Statistics by season |publisher=Croatian Football Federation |access-date=17 November 2024}}</ref> 

The 18-year-old Šunjić made his senior debut for Dinamo Zagreb on 10 May 2014, replacing [[Ante Ćorić]] after 59 minutes of a 2–1 away defeat against [[NK Istra 1961|Istra]] in the [[Croatian Football League|Prva NL]], straight after [[Jozo Šimunović]] had been [[sent off]] and Istra had tied the scores via the ensuing [[penalty kick (association football)|penalty]]. With the [[2013–14 Croatian First Football League|league title]] already secured, Dinamo fielded a weakened side for the match, with many of the regular first-team players rested between the two legs of the [[2014 Croatian Football Cup final|2014 Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://sportske.jutarnji.hr/sn/nogomet/hnl/dinamova-mladost-ipak-nije-izdrzala-istra-stigla-do-slavlja-u-revijalnoj-utakmici-u-puli-4196187 |title=Dinamova mladost ipak nije izdržala! Istra stigla do slavlja u 'revijalnoj' utakmici u Puli! |language=hr |trans-title=Dinamo's youth did not last! Istria reached the point of celebration in the 'exhibition' match in Pula! |first=Robert |last=Matteoni |newspaper=Sportske novosti |location=Zagreb |date=10 May 2014 |access-date=19 November 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.index.hr/sport/clanak/Istra-preokretom-slavila-protiv-Mamicevih-juniora/745673.aspx |title=Istra preokretom slavila protiv Mamićevih juniora |language=hr|trans-title=Istra celebrated with a reversal against Mamić's juniors |author=L.Š. |website=Index.hr |date=10 May 2014 |access-date=19 November 2024}}</ref> He helped [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb Academy#GNK Dinamo Zagreb II|Dinamo II]] gain promotion from the {{ill|2014–15 Croatian Third Football League|hr|3. HNL – Zapad 2014./15.|lt=Tréca NL in 2014–15}} and played regularly for them in the [[2015–16 Croatian Second Football League|Druga NL]], but his first-team involvement was limited to 25 minutes in an early round of the [[2015–16 Croatian Football Cup|2015–16 Croatian Cup]] before he moved on.<ref name="Semafor" />

===Lokomotiva Zagreb===
After appearing only for the reserves, he joined [[NK Lokomotiva|Lokomotiva]] on 10 February 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nogometplus.net/index.php/domaci_nogomet/ivan-sunjic-raskinuo-ugovor-s-dinamom-i-odmah-potpisao-za-lokomotivu/ |title=Ivan Šunjić raskinuo ugovor s Dinamom i odmah potpisao za Lokomotivu |language=hr | trans-title=Ivan Šunjić terminated the deal with Dinamo and immediately signed for Lokomotiva |first=Karlo |last=Propadalo |website=Nogomet Plus |date=10 February 2016 |access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref> On 13 May 2017, he scored his first goal for the club in the dying minutes of a 2–0 league victory over [[NK Inter Zaprešić|Inter Zaprešić]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nacional.hr/prva-hnl-lokomotiva-inter-2-0/ |title=Prva HNL: Lokomotiva 2–0 Inter|language=hr |magazine=Nacional |location=Zagreb |date=13 May 2017 |access-date=9 September 2018|trans-title=First HNL: Lokomotiva 2–0 Inter}}</ref>

Ahead of the [[2017–18 Croatian First Football League|2017–18 season]], Šunjić was named [[Captain (association football)|club captain]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tportal.hr/sport/clanak/nakon-sunjiceva-izbora-soudanijeva-prednost-jos-se-povecala-foto-20171128 |title=Nakon Šunjićeva izbora Soudanijeva prednost još se povećala |language=hr |trans-title=After Šunjić's election, Soudani's favor has increased |first=Silvijo |last=Škrlec|website=T-Portal|access-date=9 September 2018 |date=9 December 2017}}</ref> On 15 September, he scored the winning goal in the final minutes of a 1–0 league victory against [[HNK Cibalia|Cibalia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.glas-slavonije.hr/343265/6/Vinkovcani-imali-bod-u--dzepu-a-onda-se-pojavio--Sunjic-i-sve-pokvario |title=Vinkovčani imali bod u džepu, a onda se pojavio Šunjić i sve pokvario |language=hr |trans-title=Vinkovci had a point in their pocket, and then Sunjic appeared and everything broke down |first=Antun |last=Grgić |newspaper=Glas Slavonije |location=Osijek |date=15 September 2017 |access-date=9 September 2018 |archive-date=3 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221103182324/http://www.glas-slavonije.hr/343265/6/Vinkovcani-imali-bod-u--dzepu-a-onda-se-pojavio--Sunjic-i-sve-pokvario |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 12 February 2018, Šunjić rejoined Dinamo Zagreb and signed a contract until 15 June 2023. However, at the same time, he moved to Lokomotiva on loan for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nogometplus.net/index.php/domaci_nogomet/ivan-sunjic-potpisao-za-dinamo-ostaje-u-lokomotivi-do-kraja-sezone/ |title=Ivan Šunjić potpisao za Dinamo, ostaje u Lokomotivi do kraja sezone |language=bs |trans-title=Ivan Sunjic signed for Dinamo, staying with Lokomotiva until the end of the season |website=Nogomet Plus |date=12 February 2018 |access-date=9 September 2018}}</ref>

===Dinamo Zagreb===
Šunjić returned to Dinamo Zagreb for the [[2018–19 GNK Dinamo Zagreb season|2018–19 season]] and featured 41 times in all competitions. He made eight appearances in the [[Europa League]], scoring in a 4–1 victory against [[Fenerbahçe S.K.|Fenerbahçe]] on 20 September 2018<ref name="Dinamo Profile" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/fenerbahce-lose-to-dinamo-zagreb-in-uefa-europa-league-137071 |title=Fenerbahçe lose to Dinamo Zagreb in UEFA Europa League |newspaper=Hürriyet Daily News |agency=Anadolu |date=21 September 2018 |access-date=27 July 2019}}</ref> and starting in Dinamo Zagreb's impressive 1–0 first leg win against [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in the round of 16 of the Europa League on 7 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/match/2026903--gnk-dinamo-vs-benfica/events/ |title=UEFA Europa League: Dinamo Zagreb vs. Benfica |publisher=UEFA |date=7 March 2019 |access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> 

Šunjić was suspended for the second leg, in which Dinamo Zagreb were eliminated.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.total-croatia-news.com/sport/34679-dinamo-zagreb |title=Dinamo Zagreb exit Europa League after round of 16 loss against Benfica |first=Daniela |last=Rogulj |website=Total Croatia News |date=14 March 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |archive-date=7 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221207090742/https://www.total-croatia-news.com/sport/34679-dinamo-zagreb |url-status=dead }}</ref> He made 30 league appearances as Dinamo Zagreb [[2018–19 Croatian First Football League|finished as champions]], and scored a 90th-minute goal in the [[2018–19 Croatian Football Cup#Semi-finals|Croatian Cup semifinal]] against [[NK Osijek|Osijek]] that secured a 2–0 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.total-croatia-news.com/sport/35521-croatian-cup |title=Rijeka and Dinamo to meet in final of Croatian Cup |first=Daniela |last=Rogulj |website=Total Croatia News |date=25 April 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019 |archive-date=3 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221103182335/https://www.total-croatia-news.com/sport/35521-croatian-cup}}</ref> Šunjić started in [[2019 Croatian Football Cup Final|the final]], which Dinamo Zagreb lost 3–1 to [[HNK Rijeka|Rijeka]].<ref name="Soccerway" />

===Birmingham City===

On 26 July 2019, Šunjić signed a five-year contract with the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]. The officially undisclosed fee was reported as €7&nbsp;million.<ref name=BBCToBCFC>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49133875 |title=Ivan Sunjic: Birmingham City sign Dinamo Zagreb midfielder on five-year deal|website=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=26 July 2019 |access-date=27 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/transfer-news/birmingham-city-record-bid-accepted-16642891 |title=Birmingham City have record bid accepted for Leeds United target|first=Ben |last=Husband |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=26 July 2019 |access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> He made his debut as a second-half substitute in Birmingham's opening fixture of the season, a 1–0 win away against [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] on 3 August 2019.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49135729 |title=Brentford 0–1 Birmingham City|website=BBC Sport|publisher=BBC|date=3 August 2019 |access-date=3 August 2019}}</ref> His "rasping rising 20-yard shot which flew into the net" to tie the scores away to [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] won him the Championship Goal of the Month award for October,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11688/11837188/birmingham-midfielder-ivan-sunjic-wins-sky-bet-championship-goal-of-the-month-award-for-september |title=Birmingham midfielder Ivan Sunjic wins Sky Bet Championship Goal of the Month award for September|website=[[Sky Sports]]|date=18 October 2019 |access-date=5 July 2022}}</ref> but Birmingham lost the match.<ref name=sb1920/> 

Three months later, the ''[[Birmingham Mail]]'' rated his performance at 9/10, describing him as "imposing and dynamic" and suggesting that "the destructive side of his game [had] gone up a level",<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-player-ratings-camp-17243303 |title=Camp, Colin and Bellingham – How Birmingham City's players rate this season |first=Brian |last=Dick |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=15 November 2019 |access-date=5 July 2022}}</ref> Interviewed during the [[Timeline of the COVID-19 pandemic in England (January–June 2020)|first COVID-19 lockdown]], Šunjić felt satisfied by his season thus far, despite dips in form which he felt inevitable in a "fast, physical league" with many games, but admitted there were areas in which he could improve.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-star-nails-what-18144532 |title=Birmingham City star nails what we've all been thinking with blunt admission |first=Joseph |last=Chapman |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=24 April 2020 |access-date=5 July 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Dick |first=Brian |date=2019-11-12 |title=f168 |url=https://f168.news |access-date=2026-05-18 |language=en}}</ref> He finished the season with 44 appearances, starting in 40 of them.<ref name="sb1920" /> Šunjić joined [[Bundesliga]] club [[Hertha Berlin]] on loan for the 2022–23 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bcfc.com/news/all/ivan-sunjic-joins-hertha-berlin-on-loan |title=Ivan Sunjic joins Hertha Berlin on loan |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. |date=5 July 2022 |access-date=5 July 2022}}</ref>

Šunjić was a first team footballer during the 2023–24 season as Birmingham were relegated to the third tier for the first time in nearly 30 years.<ref name="sb2324" /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-player-ratings-norwich-29113768 |title=Alex Dicken's player ratings after Birmingham City relegated despite Norwich win |first=Alex |last=Dicken |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=4 May 2024 |access-date=1 July 2024}}</ref> He was released at the end of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bcfc.com/news/all/blues-publish-retained-and-released-players |title=Blues publish retained and released players |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. |date=18 May 2024 |access-date=1 July 2024}}</ref>

===Pafos===
Šunjić signed for [[Cyprus First Division]] club [[Pafos FC|Pafos]] on 1 August 2024.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pafosfc.com.cy/ivan-sunjic-welcome-to-pafos-fc/ |title=Ivan Šunjić, Welcome to Pafos FC! |publisher=Pafos FC |date=1 August 2024 |access-date=1 August 2024}}</ref> On 3 November 2025, Pafos announced that they had extended their contract with Šunjić until the summer of 2027.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pafos FC is pleased to announce that Ivan Šunjić has signed a contract extension with the club until 2027 |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/DQmuDuECiKl/ |website=instagram.com/pafosfc |publisher=Pafos FC Instagram |access-date=11 November 2025 |date=3 November 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
===Croatia===
[[File:20150328 1425 U19 AUTHRV 1313.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Šunjić with [[Croatia national under-19 football team|Croatia U19 in 2015]]]]

Šunjić was included in [[Croatia national under-17 football team|Croatia's squad]] for the [[2013 FIFA U-17 World Cup|2013 Under-17 World Cup]], and played all three group stage matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fifa.com/fifa-tournaments/players-coaches/people%253D372436/index.html |title=FIFA Tournaments: Players and coaches: Ivan Sunjic |publisher=FIFA |access-date=27 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911002532/http://fifa.com/fifa-tournaments/players-coaches/people%253D372436/index.html |archive-date=11 September 2015}}</ref> He was called up to the [[Croatia national football team|senior national team]] in May 2017 for a [[Exhibition game#International football|friendly match]] against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in the United States on 28 May. 

Šunjić played the whole of the match, in which an inexperienced Croatia team comprising largely debutants and reduced to ten men secured a 2–1 victory against a relatively strong Mexican team.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vecernji.hr/sport/hrvatska-u-sarenom-sastavu-protiv-neugodnog-meksika-1172651 |title=Hrvatska s 'D momčadi' i igračem manje senzacionalno pobijedila Meksiko |language=hr |trans-title=Croatia with a 'D team' and a player less sensationally beat Mexico |first=Ivan |last=Halar|newspaper=[[Večernji list]]|agency=[[Croatian News Agency]]|date=28 May 2017 |access-date=27 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.total-croatia-news.com/sport/19287-against-all-odds-young-croatian-side-defeats-mexico-in-los-angeles |title=Against all odds: young Croatian side defeats Mexico in Los Angeles! |first=Daniela |last=Rogulj |website=Total Croatia News |date=28 May 2017 |access-date=27 July 2019 |archive-date=10 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221210013056/https://www.total-croatia-news.com/sport/19287-against-all-odds-young-croatian-side-defeats-mexico-in-los-angeles}}</ref> He later served as captain of [[Croatia national under-21 football team|Croatia under-21]] at the [[2019 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] and played all three of their matches.<ref name="BBCToBCFC" /><ref name="Soccerway" />

===Bosnia and Herzegovina===
After not being called up to the Croatia senior team, Šunjić opted to switch his FIFA nationality to [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]], his country of birth. [[Sergej Barbarez]] called him up to the Bosnia and Herzegovina national team for [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League A|Nations League A]] matches against [[Germany national football team|Germany]] and the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] in November 2024.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nfsbih.ba/en/news/football-m/a-national-team-m/barbarez-announces-roster-for-november-matches/ |title=Barbarez announces roster for November matches |publisher=Bosnia and Herzegovina Football Federation|date=5 November 2024 |access-date=17 November 2024}}</ref> 

He made his debut on 16 November, starting in central midfield against Germany at [[Europa-Park Stadion]], [[Freiburg]], and played 74 minutes as Germany won 7–0, a [[UEFA Nations League|Nations League]] record.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Debitant Šunjić 'Dečki su me sjajno prihvatili, presretan sam'|url=https://www.hercegovina.info/sport/nogomet/debitant-sunjic-decki-su-me-sjajno-prihvatili-presretan-sam/230662/|website=Hercegovina.info|date=13 November 2024|access-date=10 October 2025|trans-title=Debutant Sunjic: 'The guys accepted me great, I am overjoyed'}}</ref>

